{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3d44b4b2-e6cb-4395-a0cc-e0809489f81b","content":"Yes, both are correct for .NET 10 MAUI.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This iOS platform-specific constrains page content within the safe area (avoiding the notch, Dynamic Island, home indicator, etc.). Make sure you have the namespace declared:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n         assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Added in .NET 9, this lets a specific layout break *out* of the safe area. Perfect for a full-bleed background image in a Grid while keeping other content safely inset.\n\n**Typical pattern:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background stretches edge-to-edge -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n\n        <!-- Content stays in the safe area -->\n        <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"16\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, World!\" />\n        </VerticalStackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n> **Note:** In .NET 9+ the `UseSafeArea` implementation switched from adjusting `Padding` to using iOS `SafeAreaLayoutGuide` constraints, so if your tutorial is older and suggests manually tweaking padding to complement it, that advice is outdated.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab478e52-6620-477b-a2e6-c2fbf40841d2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved:\n\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` is an iOS platform-specific that was available in earlier versions. It's a boolean attached property on `Page`.\n\n\n- `IgnoreSafeArea` was introduced later as a cross-platform property.\n\nIn .NET 9, the safe area behavior changed significantly, moving away from the `Padding` approach to a new cross-platform model for handling safe areas.\n\nIn .NET 8 and earlier, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` would adjust the page's padding to account for the safe area, but .NET 9 shifted to using `UIView.SafeAreaLayoutGuide` instead. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property was introduced in .NET 9 specifically for layouts like Grid and StackLayout, allowing them to extend beyond the safe area—particularly useful for background images that should span the full screen.\n\nFor .NET 10, both approaches should still be valid: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` at the page level to constrain content, and `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on individual layouts to break out of those constraints. I'm fairly confident about this guidance, though I want to be careful about the exact timing of when each feature was introduced. I don't need to look anything up here—this is straightforward knowledge about .NET MAUI APIs that I'm confident about.","outputTokens":1298,"requestId":"A424:D37CE:528502:6034A8:69F00894"},"id":"57950da7-2e12-4635-a0b5-e1c14e4852ac","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:09:01.964Z","parentId":"fedaa8f3-03d4-4652-b475-c2a774fd099f"}
